@node Installation
@section Installation

The fastest path is via MELPA once ELOT is accepted there.  Until
then@comma{} install from Git.

@menu
* Prerequisites::
* Install ELOT from MELPA::
* Install ELOT from Git::
* Point ELOT at ROBOT::
* Verify::
@end menu

@node Prerequisites
@subsection Prerequisites

@itemize
@item
@strong{Emacs 30.1 or later}.  ELOT uses @samp{peg.el}@comma{} which became a built-in
library in 30.1.
@item
@strong{Java 11 or later}@comma{} required by ROBOT@.
@item
@strong{@uref{https://github.com/ontodev/robot, ROBOT}}@comma{} an OWL command-line tool.  Download @samp{robot.jar} from the
ROBOT releases page and note its path.
@item
@strong{@uref{https://plantuml.com/, PlantUML}} (optional)@comma{} for diagram rendering via @samp{rdfpuml}.
@item
@strong{Protégé 5.6} (optional)@comma{} for cross-checking ontologies in a GUI@.
@end itemize

@node Install ELOT from MELPA
@subsection Install ELOT from MELPA

When ELOT is on MELPA:

@lisp
(use-package elot
  :ensure t)
@end lisp

That is the whole installation.  @samp{elot-mode} is autoloaded.

@node Install ELOT from Git
@subsection Install ELOT from Git

Until the MELPA recipe lands@comma{} clone the repository and add it to
your load path:

@example
git clone https://github.com/johanwk/elot ~/src/elot
@end example

In your @samp{init.el}:

@lisp
(add-to-list 'load-path "~/src/elot/elot-package")
(require 'elot)
@end lisp

@node Point ELOT at ROBOT
@subsection Point ELOT at ROBOT

Set @samp{elot-robot-jar-path} to the absolute path of your downloaded
@samp{robot.jar}:

@lisp
(setq elot-robot-jar-path "~/bin/robot.jar")
@end lisp

You can also customize it via @samp{M-x customize-variable RET
elot-robot-jar-path}.

@node Verify
@subsection Verify

Open an Org file and run @samp{M-x elot-mode}.  The ELOT menu appears in
the menu bar.  @samp{M-x elot-version} prints the loaded version.

If something goes wrong@comma{} see @ref{Troubleshooting and FAQ, , Troubleshooting and FAQ}.

@node Your first ontology
@section Your first ontology

In this chapter you build a tiny ontology of @emph{pets} from scratch.
By the end you will have:

@itemize
@item
a working @samp{pets.org} file you can re-tangle and re-export at will@comma{}
@item
a generated @samp{pets.omn} ontology in OWL Manchester Syntax@comma{}
@item
the start of an HTML render of your ontology document.
@end itemize

Time required: 15--20 minutes.

@menu
* Create the file::
* Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax::
* Sanity-check with ROBOT::
* Where to next::
@end menu

@node Create the file
@subsection Create the file

Create @samp{pets.org} anywhere in your filesystem and paste the
skeleton below.  Open it in Emacs and run @samp{M-x elot-mode}.

@example
#+TITLE: A tiny ontology of pets
#+AUTHOR: Your Name

* Prefixes
@comma{}:PROPERTIES:
@comma{}:header-args:emacs-lisp+: :tangle no
@comma{}:END:

#+name: prefix-table
@comma{}| prefix | uri                                            |
@comma{}|--------+------------------------------------------------|
@comma{}| ex     | http://example.org/pets/                       |
@comma{}| owl    | http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#                 |
@comma{}| rdfs   | http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#          |
@comma{}| skos   | http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#           |

* ex:pets
@comma{}:PROPERTIES:
@comma{}:ID:       pets-ontology
@comma{}:ontology-iri: http://example.org/pets/
@comma{}:END:

A small example ontology used by the ELOT tutorial.

** Classes
*** ex:Animal
A living creature.

*** ex:Dog
@comma{}:PROPERTIES:
@comma{}:subclass-of: ex:Animal
@comma{}:END:
A dog is an animal.

*** ex:Cat
@comma{}:PROPERTIES:
@comma{}:subclass-of: ex:Animal
@comma{}:END:
A cat is an animal.
@end example

@node Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax
@subsection Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax

With point anywhere in @samp{pets.org}@comma{} run @samp{M-x elot-tangle}.  A file
@samp{pets.omn} appears next to your Org source.  Open it; you should
see Manchester-syntax declarations for @samp{ex:Animal}@comma{} @samp{ex:Dog} and
@samp{ex:Cat}.

@node Sanity-check with ROBOT
@subsection Sanity-check with ROBOT

From a shell:

@example
robot report --input pets.omn --output pets-report.tsv
@end example

ROBOT's report should be empty (or contain only INFO entries).
Errors mean ELOT generated something OWL does not like; see
@ref{Linting and syntax checking, , Linting and syntax checking}.

